    "每日开盘价"
  ],
  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "The opening price of the current daily candle at 00:00 EST, marked as a horizontal level on intraday charts. It serves as a key intraday reference, acting as a magnet target during consolidation profiles, a premium/discount divider, and a support/resistance level. After large-wick reversal candles, price commonly retraces toward the daily open and reacts upon contact.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Mark a horizontal line at the opening price of the current daily candle (00:00 EST) on the lower time frame chart.",
    "During a Seek and Destroy profile, note when price deviates outside a defined range (Asia or London range) and observe whether it returns toward the Daily Open level.",
    "Use the Power of Three indicator or session boxes to visually anchor the Daily Open relative to intraday session highs and lows.",
    "Confirm the Daily Open is acting as a magnet when price repeatedly exits a range and rebalances back to this level across multiple sessions within the same day.",
    "After a reversal, treat the daily open as a liquidity draw and potential support/resistance, often in conjunction with nearby failure swings.",
    "Observe price reaction on retests of the daily open; rejection confirms its role as support/resistance.",
    "Use the daily open as a premium/discount divider: in a bearish context, price above is premium; in a bullish context, price below is discount.",
    "Anticipate the daily candle's OHLC sequence around the daily open: bullish days form open–low–high–close, bearish days form open–high–low–close.",
    "When a daily reversal candle forms with a large wick, expect retracement toward the daily open rather than full expansion, especially after lower time frame CISD confirmation.",
    "If a protected intraday swing exists near the daily open, prioritize the daily open as a target over more distant liquidity levels.",
    "Identify daily K-line with large wick (especially opposite to body direction) indicating insufficient expansion momentum; when daily does not support expansion, mark daily open as target.",
    "Combine session lows as additional target area reference."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "The daily open frames intraday bias and target placement. During consolidation profiles, it acts as a primary magnet target when price deviates outside a range; traders anticipate a return toward the daily open rather than a sustained breakout. In bullish contexts, expect a move below into discount before expansion; in bearish contexts, a move above into premium before reversal. After a reversal, project from the manipulation leg to the daily open as a primary target, often alongside failure swings or fair value gaps. It acts as support/resistance on retests, ideal for partials or exits. After large-wick reversal candles, target the daily open instead of distant extremes to manage risk against failed expansions.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Treating the Daily Open as a directional bias signal rather than a consolidation magnet, leading to premature breakout trades that fail.",
    "Ignoring the Daily Open as a target when trading range extremes during consolidation days, causing traders to hold for larger expansions that do not materialize.",
    "Confusing a small close relative to the Daily Open (e.g., 80 points on NQ) with a directional day, when it actually confirms a Seek and Destroy / indecision profile.",
    "Expecting full expansion after a large wick reversal instead of targeting the daily open retracement.",
    "Ignoring whether price is above or below the daily open for premium/discount assessment, leading to wrong-side entries.",
    "Confusing the daily open with the 9:30 NYSE open or assuming it is identical across all asset classes (e.g., Forex daily opens differ).",
    "Entering a reversal trade without lower time frame confirmation (CISD) of the daily reversal candle.",
    "Failing to adjust targets based on daily candle characteristics (large wick vs small wick), leading to overly aggressive targets.",
    "Still expecting price to reach prior highs or distant targets when daily does not support expansion, instead of reverting to daily open."
  ],
